#### [NEW] [index.js](file:///c:/Users/hp/Desktop/Et-AI_Hack/ET-AI-Hack/whatsapp-bridge/index.js)

Main entry point. Architecture:

```
WhatsApp Bridge (:3001)
├── Express REST API
│   ├── GET  /status          → { connected, qrReady, phone }
│   ├── GET  /chats           → list all chats with metadata
│   ├── GET  /chats/:id       → messages for a specific chat
│   ├── POST /disconnect      → logout WhatsApp session
│   └── GET  /health          → health check
├── WebSocket Server (/ws)
│   ├── event: "qr"           → QR code data URL pushed to frontend
│   ├── event: "authenticated" → session authenticated
│   ├── event: "ready"        → client ready, can fetch chats
│   ├── event: "message"      → new incoming message (real-time)
│   └── event: "disconnected" → session ended
└── WhatsApp Client (whatsapp-web.js)
    ├── LocalAuth strategy (persistent session in .wwebjs_auth/)
    ├── QR code generation on init
    ├── Chat fetching (all chats, paginated messages)
    └── Real-time message listener
```

Key implementation details:
- On startup, initialize `whatsapp-web.js` `Client` with `LocalAuth` for session persistence
- On `qr` event: convert QR string to data URL using `qrcode` package, push via WebSocket
- On `ready` event: notify all connected WS clients
- **`GET /chats`**: Call `client.getChats()`, return `{ id, name, isGroup, timestamp, unreadCount, lastMessage }`
- **`GET /chats/:id`**: Call `chat.fetchMessages({ limit: 100 })`, return `{ id, from, body, timestamp, fromMe, type }`
- **Real-time**: Listen to `client.on('message')`, broadcast to WS clients
- Port: `3001` (configurable via env)

